Charp's character popularity ranking is derived from FineFreq, a table of
per-code-point frequency counts computed over the FineWeb and FineWeb2 web
corpora (themselves built from Common Crawl).

    FineFreq — https://huggingface.co/datasets/lgi2p/finefreq
    © Binbin Xu, licensed under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International
    (CC BY 4.0) — https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/

    Binbin Xu. FineFreq: A Multilingual Character Frequency Dataset from
    Web-Scale Text. arXiv:2512.09701 (2025).

Charp uses the English-language frequency table to compute the order of the
characters in src/characters.json. The dataset itself is not redistributed; only
the derived ordering is embedded, and the dataset is not modified.

---

Charp's ranking of the compatibility characters that NFKC normalization removes
from FineFreq (™, ½, …, and other folded forms) is derived from the Leipzig
Corpora Collection (English news and web corpora), whose non-normalized text
preserves them.

    Leipzig Corpora Collection — https://wortschatz.uni-leipzig.de
    © Universität Leipzig, licensed under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0
    International (CC BY 4.0) — https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/

    D. Goldhahn, T. Eckart & U. Quasthoff. Building Large Monolingual
    Dictionaries at the Leipzig Corpora Collection: From 100 to 200 Languages.
    Proceedings of the 8th International Conference on Language Resources and
    Evaluation (LREC 2012).

Only per-code-point counts derived from these corpora are committed (as
src/leipzig-freq.json); the corpora themselves are not redistributed.
